## History
- First 400 years of the republic go great!
	- Conquered lots of land
	- Somewhat peaceful times (internally at least)
- Last 100 years shit hits the fan 
	- Civil war, chaos, massacres
- Western Roman Empire collapsed in the 400s, officially ended in 476
	- Potentially influenced by lead poisoning, from lead water pipes



## Hellenization
- [[Unsorted/Ancient Greeks\|Greek]] culture significantly influenced Roman ideas
	- When [[Unsorted/Ancient Greeks\|Greece]] was captured by Rome, much of their culture spilled out into Roman territory
	- Adopted the entire [[Unsorted/Ancient Greeks\|Greek]] pantheon, altering some of the names
		- Still referred to as the "12 Gods Religion"
- Incredibly influential in their ideas about politics, law, military, engineering, and science
- And many [[Unsorted/Ancient Greeks\|Greek]] ideas were directly translated into Roman versions
	- Adopted the entire [[Unsorted/Ancient Greeks\|Greek]] pantheon, altering some of the names
	- Adopted many [[Unsorted/Ancient Greeks\|Greek]] myths
		- Such as the rape of persephone



## Temples of Pluto (Hades)
- Temples were built around caves, supposed entrances to [[Class - Roots of Hell/Punishing afterlife\|Hades (Place)]], known as a "Plutonium"
	- Bulls were offered as sacrifices to Pluto
		- When put in the cave, they collapsed and died
			- Believed to be the breath of cerberus
			- Built over fissures that filled the caves entirely with CO2
				- Because it's dense, it visibly pools under air in dark cool places
			- Priests were just taller, heads were out of the CO2
			- To this day, birds that enter the cave die
		- What happens to the bulls after?
			- Their bodies wouldn't decompose properly, due to lack of oxygen
			- And the priests couldn't just bend down and pick them up
			- Perhaps the bull's rich fermentation-based guts had microbes that could decompose it?
			- Maybe they just kicked them deeper into the caves

# Philosophical movements

## Stoicism
- Very popular in rome
- Marcus Aurelius
- Didn't care about the afterlife
	- Believed that the soul evaporates at [[Unsorted/Death\|Death]]

## Neoplatonism
- Newer take on Platonism from [[Unsorted/Ancient Greeks\|Greece]]
- Argued that all souls were reincarnated
	- Fitting hosts
	- Believed that eventually everyone merges with [[Unsorted/God (Monotheistic)\|The One]]
		- Less an individual and more of a cosmic force
- Evil does not exist: The absence of good

## Emperor worship
- Starting with Julius Caesar
- Believed that they became [[God (Polytheistic)\|gods]] when they died
- Happened after [[Unsorted/The Egyptians\|Egyptian]] contact

# Influential figures


### Virgil

- Magnum opus: The Aeneid
	- Long-form poem, written around 30BCE
	- Linguistically beautiful, marvel of classical latin
	- A "National epic poem of ancient Rome"
	- Focuses on character Aeneas, a great warrior from the [[Unsorted/Trojan War\|Trojan War]]
		- Managed to flee Troy while it was being slaughtered and razed
			- Somewhere in the carnage, loses his wife
			- With a small group of survivors
		- Travelled all over the Mediterranean Sea
			- Went to Carthage at some point
				- Carthage is the greatest threat to Roman dominance
					- Nearly conquered Rome centuries earlier
						- Virgil depicted Carthage far before that war
							- Used to give the dead the powers of accurate prophecy
				- Welcomed by Dido, queen of Carthage
					- Impressed by eachother
						- Aeneas is famous from the [[Unsorted/Trojan War\|Trojan War]]
					- Some romance, but they keep at a distance for political reasons
				- They go on a hunt, and the hunting party is dispersed and fractured by a large storm
					- Dido and Aenas find eachother, then find a cave and they can finally fuck
					- Both of them wanted to stay in Carthage as married partners
						- But the gods insist that he continues his journey because he will eventually found Rome
							- Dido is devastated, feels betrayed, commits suicice on a funeral pyre
								- While dying, utters a curse promising that Carthage will destroy Rome, and there will never be peace between them
							- Dido later appears in [[Unsorted/Dante's Inferno\|Dante's Inferno]], in the circle of lust and not the [circle of suicide]
			- Arrives in Italy, where Rome has not yet been founded
				- The dead father of Aeneas appears to him in a dream
				- Says they must talk, and that he may do it in [[Class - Roots of Hell/Punishing afterlife\|Hades (Place)]]
			- The Sibyl of Cumae (seer/oracle) tells Aeneas what he needs to do
				- Was a real person
					- Wrote / was written about in 9 books known as "The Sibylline Books"
				- Offers to be his guide
					- But insists that first he needs a *golden bough* (branch), or else he will not be able to return
						- If it breaks off easily, the gods are okay with it
						- If it doesn't, the gods are not and he needs to cancel the journey
			- They enter the [[Unsorted/Common features of Hell#Gates guardians\|Gates]] of Dis into the [[Class - Roots of Hell/Punishing afterlife\|the underworld]]
	- One of the most detialed, colorful depictions of [[Class - Roots of Hell/Punishing afterlife\|Hell]]
		- ![Pasted image 20220926153225.png|200](data:image/png;base64,)
		- Describes a number of monsters and anthropomorphisms of many concepts
			- Such as sleep, death, war, toil, dread, hunger, grief, discord
		- They reach [[Unsorted/Common features of Hell#A Boat Boatman\|Charon]] at [[Unsorted/Common features of Hell#A River\|The Archeron River]]
			- A crowd of souls is waiting at the boat, Aeneas recognizes one, Palinurus
				- Says he was the helmsman of Aeneas' ship, fell asleep and into the water
				- And that he floated around for 3 days before finally dying
				- On the 4th day, he saw land and swam to shore
					- But was killed by the inhabitants
					- And his body is still there on the beach, unburied
						- So he doesn't have a coin to pay the fare
						- One of the greatest Roman and [[Unsorted/Ancient Greeks\|Greek]] taboos was to leave a body unburied
							- And that their souls took the form of Lemures
								- Angry, vengeful and restless
							- HOWEVER, Palinurus is told that he will be able to cross anyways after 100 years of waiting
				- Anaeas asks about the many souls who cannot cross
					- Pauper souls, unburied
			- Charon notices that Aeneas and Sibyl are living, but [[Unsorted/Psychopomp\|Charon]] lets them cross anyways
		- Across the river:
			- Many souls of those waiting to be [[Unsorted/Afterlives#Sorting\|Sorted]]
			- Sees Dido among them in the Field of Mourning, and speaks to her
				- She turns away and leaves, Aeneas weeps
			- Continues to the Field of Warriors
				- Sees many comrades and foes
			- Looks at Tartarus
				- Wide battlements, triple wall
				- Gate made of pillars of solid steel
					- *Note: Steel was VERY uncommon in Rome, they preferred bronze*
						- Steel is a Greek loanword, they had better metallurgy
				- Characters
					- Tisiphone
						- "Voice of Revenge," a fury, who avenges murder
							- The furies are an analog to guilt
								- The Greeks/romans didn't have the terminology or tools to study psychology, so these myths were their best ways to depict them
					- Says that beyond the gate, Rhadamanthus judges the most evil souls
						- The worst go to an abyss twice as deep as the earth is distant from the skies
					- Guarded by the hydra
				- The sound of whippings and chains travel far outside the walls 
				- Sibyl lists the people who suffer there.
					- Those who:
						- Hated their brothers
						- Struct their parents
						- Engaged in incest or adultery
						- Accepted bribes
						- Defrauded inheritence
						- Deserted
					- Generally, violations of family boundaries
					- *No direct mention of murder?*
					- She stops because the list is very long
						- "Not if she had a hundred tongues and mouths"
		- They arrive at the [[Unsorted/Rewarding afterlife\|Elysian fields]]
			- He meets with the shade of his father
			- Who lays out the future of Aeneas, his descendants, and Rome
				- Very accurate prophecies, since they'd already happened
				- One of his descendants, several generations later, is Romulus, who founds Rome
				- Quickly covers Roman history
					- Caesar
				- Describes feats of the future
					- Future [[Unsorted/Ancient Greeks\|Greeks]]
						- Hammer out bronz ethat breathes with more delicacy than us
						- Draw out living features from marble
						- Plead their causes better
						- Trace the movements of the skies with instruments
					- Rome
						- Rule the nations with your power
						- Crown peace with law
						- Spare the conquered
						- Subdue the proud/arrogant
		- Aeneas goes back to the surface and continues his destiny
			- It's an unfinished poem!
				- Virgil died while writing it
					- Gave instructions to his scribes/secretaries to finish the poem without him if he dies
					- But Augustus demanded they didn't
			- Was approached by Augustus Caesar, asked to make an epic poem about Augustus
				- Said he had one already that could include him, but did not focus on him
				- About the foundation of Rome
				- Augustus was fine with that

#### Virgil's future influence
- Hugely influential for later writers and thinkers
	- Centuries later, [[Unsorted/Descent Protagonist\|Dante]] chose Virgil to be his [[Unsorted/Psychopomp\|Psychopomp]] to accompany him to [[Class - Roots of Hell/Punishing afterlife\|Hell]]



### Plutarch
- 45-120CE
- Wrote lots of biographies about ancient figures
- Wrote about Thespesius in *On the Slowness of Divine Justice*
	
##### On the Slowness of Divine Justice
- One of the first accounts of a [[Unsorted/Hell Tropes#Near Death Experience\|Near Death Experience]]
- Very different than traditional versions of hell or Virgil's
- Focuses on Thespesius
	- Led a debauched and intempreate life in youth
		- "Abstained from nothing that was lewd and illegal"
		- Believed to have hooked up with married women, and blackmailed them for money
	- Spent all his inheritance
- Thespesius visits an [[Unsorted/Prophet\|oracle]] to hear his future
	- "Will I live any better for the reamining part of my life?"
		- "Things will go better for you after you are dead"
- Fell from a high place and dies
	- No injuries, but he isn't breathing
	- After 3 days was taken to be buried
		- Woke up just when they were lowering him down
		- His personality is completely different
			- More just, better friend
			- Claims it's because he remembers what happened when he died
- At the start of his vision:
	- Felt like he was flung into the sea
	- Surfaced and "opened..one eye of his soul"
	- Saw stars, extremely large and distant from eachother
		- Vivid forceful light
		- Similar to our modern understanding of the universe
		- There were souls on those beams, moving smoothly and gently, but extremely quickly
	- He sees some newly-dead souls
		- Look like fiery bubbles
			- They dissolve and a humanoid soul emerges
		- Some were very agile, and formed orderly lines
		- Others are confused, hesitant
			- They spin around and fly in random directions
				- Seemed insane, shouted out in fear or lament
			- He recognizes some of his acquaintences in this group
			- They ignored him
				- Couldn't hear him or didn't care
		- Both groups crowd together
	- One of the orderly souls, a relative that died when he was young, comes to explain
		- Says he's not dead yet
			- Only his intellect is there
			- But the rest of the soul is still there in his body
		- And that he's there by permission of the gods
		- Says that Adrastea is the ruler of this place
			- The daughter of Jupiter (Zeus) and the anthropomorphization of Necessity
			- There to "punish all manner of crimes and enormities"
				- No souls, no matter their power in life, could escape her
	- Punishments are divided into 3 groups
		1. Each has a Fury (Female justice administers) 
		- Speedy punishment
			- For those who have already suffered during their lives
		- Justice
			- More severe
			- For those who escaped punishment on Earth
			- If the wrongdoer's parents were virtuous, they are shown what their kid has become
				- If they're both wicked, they see eachother
					- Until each individual undergoes immense suffering to make up for thier wrongdoings
		- Erinnys (THE fury)
			- For the worst of the worst
			- Chased without hope of shelter or relief
				- When caught, tormented with 1000 miseries
			- Then plunged headfirst into an infinite, invisible abyss
				- Indescribably hideous
	- He comes to a place where he sees his friends and family being tormented horribly
		- Is confronted by his dad
			- Mangled, gashed, scarred
			- Not permitted to stay silent: MUST confess crimes
				- Poisoned several guests to get their gold
				- He got away with it, so he's being punished more severely
		- Pushed along by goblins to see more
	- Symbolic punishments:
		- Some souls are twisted into eachother
			- Gnawing and devouring eachother
			- Grudges that existed before the afterlife
		- Those who feigned virtue while truly being wicked beneath
			- Were turned inside out, extremely painful
		- 3 lakes for those who were greedy and envious
			- Lakes of...
				- boiling gold
				- freezing lead
				- scaly and rugged iron
			- Patrolled by demons with blacksmith tools
				- Breaking down and transforming souls as if they are metal
		- Those who harmed children
			- The most severely punished
			- Child abuse has only been considered bad particularly recently
			- Abuse, or not leaving any inheritance
			- Surrounded by those suffering children
				- Swarm like bees or bats
				- Angrily complain about the harm done 
					- Bitter taunts
	- Was whirled away by a wind back into his body
		- Travelled through a sort of pipe on the way out
			- Light at the end of the tunnel?
